    cellular: { title: "Foundations of Therapeutic Communication in Nursing", content: "Therapeutic communication is a purposeful, goal-directed form of professional communication that focuses on the patient's needs and promotes healing, safety, and trust. Unlike social communication, therapeutic communication has a specific purpose: gathering health information, providing education, offering emotional support, and facilitating informed decision-making.\n\nKey elements include: (1) Active listening — attending to both verbal and nonverbal messages, providing undivided attention, and using minimal encouragers ('go on,' 'tell me more'). (2) Empathy — understanding and acknowledging the patient's feelings without judgment ('I can see this is very difficult for you'). (3) Open-ended questions — questions that cannot be answered with yes/no and encourage the patient to elaborate ('How are you feeling about your diagnosis?'). (4) Reflection — restating the patient's feelings or content to demonstrate understanding ('It sounds like you are frustrated with the treatment plan'). (5) Clarification — seeking additional information to ensure accurate understanding ('Can you tell me more about what you mean by dizzy?'). (6) Silence — allowing pauses for the patient to collect thoughts and process emotions.\n\nBarriers to therapeutic communication include: providing false reassurance ('Everything will be fine'), giving advice ('You should...'), changing the subject when the patient is expressing concerns, using medical jargon, being judgmental, and asking 'why' questions (can feel accusatory). The SBAR tool (Situation, Background, Assessment, Recommendation) standardizes professional communication between healthcare providers for patient safety." },
